06/12/23, 12:18 pm - Sunny '22: Hello guys, you guys must be knowing that placements are going on and must've gone through the mails sent by TPO of the highest and the lowest packages offered. Those figures are true and we should be proud of our TPO for producing such high numbers even in this economic recession. However, the problem lies in the % of the students placed and scenes for our department haven't been convincing to say the least.
Companies are looking at both CPI and Skillsets of the students before hiring and prioritising quality over quantity. In these times just being an IITian is not enough, you have to be skilled as well. There are plenty of opportunities but the thing is some students are not skilled enough as per the company standards.
Guys please start thinking over what profile you want to pursue and in which field you want to pursue your career in and work accordingly. Start putting in efforts from now for the placements and intern season.

Ceramic Engineering part II

Having had the honor of serving as a Training and Placement Volunteer with the Training and Placement Cell for the past twelve months, I've witnessed firsthand the remarkable influence it has on our students and institute. The TPC's exceptional professionalism and dynamic atmosphere distinguish it as a standout entity within our institution. The unwavering dedication and drive of its members to continuously strive for improvement inspire me to redouble my efforts in contributing to our shared mission.

I am pleased to express my intent to apply for the Training and Placement Representative of Ceramic Engineering in the upcoming academic session 2024-25.

Having worked as a TPV for a year gave me insight into the working environment of TPC and allowed me to work with some of the most committed seniors in the college. In the phase II of placements I was tasked with assisting my senior Mr. Manan Gupta in managing the venue logistics for all the internships and placements of 2023-2024 , the responsibility of coordinating tests and interviews alongside the scheduling team, ensuring smooth operations throughout. Apart from it , I was one of the volunteers which had one of the highest test duty counts showcasing my work ethic towards TPC. 

In addition to my involvement with the Training and Placement Cell, I have actively participated in various campus initiatives such as the FMC Weekend and Model United Nations, where I have honed my skills in team management and leadership. These experiences have equipped me with a diverse set of capabilities that I am eager to bring to the role of Training and Placement Representative within the Training and Placement Cell.
 
Given my background and experiences, I am confident that I possess the necessary skills and strengths to excel in the role of Training and Placement Representative within the Training and Placement Cell. If entrusted with this opportunity, I am fully committed to meeting and exceeding the expectations and responsibilities associated with the position, demonstrating unwavering dedication and diligence.

Myself Abhirvey Iyer, am a student at IIT(BHU) Varanasi specializing in Pharmaceutical Engineering and Technology.

I am currently looking for an internship in the field of Data Analytics/ Machine Learning for the summer months of May, June, and July.

Currently, I have a good hold of the essential data visualization tools, SQL, Power BI, and Excel, and I am also in the process of learning ML. In ML, I have learned Linear Regression, Logistic Regression, Feature Engineering, Cross Validation, K-Means Clustering, Decision Tree Regression, Random Forest Regression, and XGBoost and will also complete topics like Time Series Forecasting in the coming months.  Adding to this, I’ve also participated in many case competitions to develop sound business acumen. 

Recently, I also got the opportunity to represent my college at the Inter IIT Tech Meet 11.0, held at IITK. The problem statement I worked on revolved around data, bayesian networks and model building to automate complex decisions in the industry. I got a good amount of exposure to Bayesian Networks during this project and it also help me realise how crucial Machine Learning is in order to reduce the complexity of a process.

Ma'am, please do consider my application and let me know if there are any such openings under you, it would be really a great value addition for me if I get the opportunity to work under you and I will give my 100% to anything that comes my way. Looking forward to hearing from you.

My passion lies in this field of Data Analysis, Machine Learning , Business Strategy  and their application in fields of health and sports. Previously, I have worked on a project predicting Life Expectancy using regression techniques. I have also solved Business Case Studies on Market Entry for Startups . Being an ardent Chess enthusiast, my interest in Artificial Intelligence stemmed from watching neural networks like Alphazero beat the greatest chess players of our times. I also worked on a project about simulating Order Status for a food delivery app. Currently , I am exploring more in the field of NLP and Deep Learning.

Studying at an institute like IIT BHU, I have developed a strong technical base and a passion to pursue research. I believe my interests match with your research and that my knowledge combined with my enthusiasm will make me a valuable asset for your research.

31/03/24, 11:37 am - Parth +1 Cera: It was the mid sixteenth century. The Bees were prepared to crush the Red Devils. Devils, although huge and mighty, were swallowed in their own pride. The poison of pride, only a few knew. The game was all set but done. 
The Bees were favourites; the Reds oblivious. Thousands of spectators gathered at the stadium of Goliath. Hoping for their team to win, unaware of the curse of the purple cornflower, yet another fate of twist. 

The trumpets blew, the bells rang, crickets chirped at nearby land. The ball started rolling. The Bees in control. Comfortable, unruffled, yet a nervous demeanor amongst the fans.

Attack after attack after attack. The Bees pressed and pressed. The Reds fallen, taken aback. The pride was fading, horror lurked ahead of them. But the curse prevailed.

Sheer luck, they survived. Survived the attack, the attempts, the shots taken. It was all set for a stalemate, but fate was dismayed. 

The Bees lit the cannons, marched forward to rule. With guards down, palace left undefended, the Reds took their chance. 

And broke the curse of the yellow sunflower. Or purple whatever. The Bees marched forward, fired the shot, stole the gold. While the Reds still celebrated their only goal.

The trumpets blew again, marked the end of an incredible war. Fans frustrated, yet delighted. A juxtaposition of joy and despair, hearts not wretched, with glimmer of hope of a brighter tomorrow.
